==History==

{{further information|History of chess}}
[[File:Grose-Francis-Pavisors-and-Moveable-Tower-Assaulting-Castle-1812.jpg|thumb|Illustration of a [[siege tower]], which the rook may be intended to represent]]
In the medieval [[shatranj]], the rook symbolized a '''[[chariot]]'''. The [[Persian language|Persian]] word ''rukh'' means &quot;chariot&quot;{{harvcol|Davidson|1949|p=10}}, and the corresponding piece in the original Indian version, [[chaturanga]], has the name ''ratha'' (meaning &quot;chariot&quot;). In modern times it is mostly known as हाथी ([[elephant]]) to [[hindi (language)|Hindi]]-speaking players, while east-Asian chess games such as [[xiangqi]] and [[shogi]] have names also meaning chariot (車) for the same piece.&lt;ref&gt;現代漢語詞典 {{ISBN|978-962-07-0211-2}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Persian war-chariots were heavily armored, carrying a driver and at least one ranged-weapon bearer, such as an archer. The sides of the chariot were built to resemble fortified stone work, giving the impression of small, mobile buildings, causing terror on the battlefield.

In Europe the castle or tower appears for the first time in the 16th century in [[Marco Girolamo Vida | Vida]]'s 1550 ''Ludus Scacchia'', and then as a tower on the back of an elephant. In time, the elephant disappeared and only the tower was used as the piece.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | title= Article by Dr. Hans Holländer, &quot;CYCLOPES, ELEPHANTS AND CHESS ROOKS&quot; |url= http://www.chess-museum.com/cyclopes-elephants-and-chess-rooks-by-hans-hollaumlnder.html |accessdate= 26 February 2020}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In the West, the rook is almost universally represented as a [[crenellation |crenellated]] [[turret]]. The piece is called ''torre'' (&quot;tower&quot;) in Italian, Portuguese, and Spanish; ''tour'' in French; ''toren'' in Dutch; ''Turm'' in German; ''torn'' in Swedish; and ''torni'' in Finnish. In Hungarian it is ''bástya'' (&quot;[[bastion]]&quot;) and in [[Hebrew language]] it is called ''צריח'' (pronounced &quot;Tzariach&quot;, meaning &quot;fortified tower&quot;). In the [[British Museum]]'s collection of the medieval [[Lewis chessmen |Lewis chess pieces]] the rooks appear as stern warders, or wild-eyed [[Berserker]] warriors.

Rooks usually are similar in appearance to small castles, and as a result a rook is sometimes called a &quot;'''castle'''&quot; {{harvcol|Hooper|Whyld|1996}}.
Modern chess literature rarely, if ever, uses this term.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Horton|1959|p= 175}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In some languages the rook is called a '''ship''': Thai เรือ (''reūa''), [[Armenian language |Armenian]] Նավակ (''navak''), Russian ладья (''ladya''), [[Javanese language| Javanese]] ꦥꦫꦄꦲꦸ (''prahu''). This may be because of the use of an Arabic style V-shaped rook piece, which some may have mistaken for a ship.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=MpooAQAAIAAJ&amp;q=%D0%9B%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%8C%D1%8F+|title= Studia Etymologica Cracoviensia|first= Marek|last= Stachowski|date= January 4, 2002|publisher= Ksie̦garnia Akademicka|via= Google Books}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url= https://www.siamsport.co.th/column/detail/68913|title= ม้า...เสน่ห์หมากรุก|date= January 14, 2018|website= www.siamsport.co.th}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url= https://chessschool.am/lesson/15|title= Շախմատային նավակ|first= AIST|last= Global|website= chessschool.am}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;:0&quot;&gt;{{Cite book|last= Davidson|first= Henry A.|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PQBpr6KAdHkC&amp;q=javanese+word+for+chariot&amp;pg=PT66|title= A Short History of Chess|date= 2012-10-10|publisher= Crown|isbn= 978-0-307-82829-3|language= en}}&lt;/ref&gt; It is possible that the rendition comes from Sanskrit ''roka'' (ship); however, no ''chaturanga'' pieces were ever called a ''roka''. Murray argued that the [[Javanese people| Javanese]] could not visualize a chariot moving through the jungles in sweeping fashion as the rook. The only vehicle that moved in straight fashion was ship, thus they replaced it with [[Proa| prahu]]. Murray, however, did not give an explanation of why the Russians call the piece a &quot;ship&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;:0&quot; /&gt;

In Bulgarian, it is called the '''cannon''' (Топ, Romanised ''top'').

In [[Kannada language |Kannada]], it is known as ಆನೆ (''āāne''), meaning &quot;'''elephant'''&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url= https://www.english-kannada.com/|title= English :: Kannada Online Dictionary|website=English :: Kannada Online Dictionary}}&lt;/ref&gt; This is unusual, as the term for &quot;elephant&quot; is in many other languages applied to the [[bishop (chess)| bishop]].&lt;ref&gt;
{{Cite journal|title= How the Elephant became a Bishop: An Enquiry into the Origin of the Names of Chess Pieces|first= Howard|last= Candler|date= January 1, 1907|journal= Archaeological Journal|volume= 64|issue= 1|pages= 80–90|doi= 10.1080/00665983.1907.10853048 |url = https://zenodo.org/record/2238958}}
&lt;/ref&gt;

===Name translations===
