==Heraldry==
[[Image:Arms of the Rookwood family of Stanningfield.png|right|thumb|200px|Arms of the English family of Rookwood, featuring chess rooks as a [[canting arms|cant]] on the name]] Chess rooks frequently occur as heraldic [[charge (heraldry)|charges]]. Heraldic rooks are usually shown as they looked in medieval chess-sets, with the usual battlements replaced by two outward-curving horns. They occur in arms from around the 13th&amp;nbsp;century onwards.

In [[Canadian heraldry]], the chess rook is the [[cadency]] mark of a fifth daughter.

