The '''bishop''' (♗,♝) is a [[Chess piece|piece]] in the game of [[chess]]. Each player begins the game with two bishops. One starts between the {{chessgloss|king's knight}} and the [[King (chess)|king]], the other between the {{chessgloss|queen's knight}} and the [[Queen (chess)|queen]]. The starting squares are c1 and f1 for White's bishops, and c8 and f8 for Black's bishops.
{{AN chess|pos=toc}}

==Placement and movement==
The bishop has no restrictions in distance for each move, but is limited to [[diagonal]] movement. Bishops, like all other pieces except the [[Knight (chess)|knight]], cannot jump over other pieces. A bishop captures by occupying the square on which an enemy piece sits.

The bishops may be differentiated according to which wing they begin on, i.e. the ''king's bishop'' and ''queen's bishop''. As a consequence of its diagonal movement, each bishop always remains on either the white or black squares, and so it is also common to refer to them as ''light-squared'' or ''dark-squared'' bishops.

